aa(lp142
VNow, I want to emphasize that these are just examples.
p143
aVI'm not holding these out as being the biggest issues.
p144
aVThey're just examples.
p145
aVAnd the reason that I do this, it's because I have this fear
p146
aVthat we aren't feeling enough as a culture right now.
p147
aVThere's this kind of anesthesia in America at the moment.
p148
aVWe've lost our sense of outrage, our anger and our grief
p149
aVabout what's going on in our culture right now,
p150
aVwhat's going on in our country,
p151
aVthe atrocities that are being committed in our names around the world.
p152
aVThey've gone missing; these feelings have gone missing.
p153
aVOur cultural joy, our national joy is nowhere to be seen.
p154
aVAnd one of the causes of this, I think,
p155
aVis that as each of us attempts to build this new kind of worldview,
p156
aVthis holoptical worldview, this holographic image
p157
aVthat we're all trying to create in our mind
p158
aVof the interconnection of things: the environmental footprints
p159
aV1,000 miles away of the things that we buy;
p160
aVthe social consequences 10,000 miles away
p161
aVof the daily decisions that we make as consumers.
p162
aa(lp163
VAs we try to build this view,
p164
aVand try to educate ourselves about the enormity of our culture,
p165
aVthe information that we have to work with is these gigantic numbers:
p166
aVnumbers in the millions, in the hundreds of millions,
p167
aVin the billions and now in the trillions.
p168
aVBush's new budget is in the trillions, and these are numbers
p169
aVthat our brain just doesn't have the ability to comprehend.
p170
